{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585098"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:03:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:03:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14862"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14862"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.05,0.02,0.79,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63514"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7553"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14862"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48968"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"83"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10909"},{"type":"tags","id":"10913"},{"type":"tags","id":"10914"},{"type":"tags","id":"10915"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18541"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63514"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESeveral neurodegenerative conditions share similar pathological features including spongiform changes in brain tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pathogens causes Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, Kuru, and Bovine spongiform encephalopathy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flatworms","Nematodes","Roundworms","Prions","Protozoa"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECJD is a human prion disease that leads to rapid neurodegeneration. Kuru was historically found in Papua New Guinea and was linked to cannibalistic practices. BSE, also known as mad cow disease, affects cattle and can be transmitted to humans as variant CJD. They are all examples of \u003Cstrong\u003Eprion\u003C/strong\u003E diseases. Prions are infectious protein particles that lack nucleic acid and cause transmissible spongiform encephalopathies through protein misfolding. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlatworms\u003C/strong\u003E (platyhelminths), \u003Cstrong\u003Enematodes\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eroundworms\u003C/strong\u003E are parasitic worms that can affect humans but do not cause spongiform encephalopathies. \u003Cstrong\u003EProtozoa\u003C/strong\u003E are single-celled eukaryotic organisms that can cause various diseases but are not responsible for these specific conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrion diseases are characterized by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccumulation of misfolded prion proteins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpongiform degeneration of brain tissue\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELong incubation periods\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProgressive and always fatal course\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENo inflammatory response\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prions are infectious proteins that cause transmissible spongiform encephalopathies including Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, kuru, and bovine spongiform encephalopathy.","Prions are unique pathogens that contain no genetic material and propagate by inducing normal proteins to misfold."],"references":["Atlas, R. M., \u0026 Snyder, J. W. (2013). Handbook of media for clinical and public health microbiology. CRC Press","Johnson RT. Prion diseases. Lancet Neurol. 2005 Oct;4(10):635-42. doi: 10.1016/S1474-4422(05)70192-7. PMID: 16168932.","Baiardi S, Mammana A, Capellari S, Parchi P. Human prion disease: molecular pathogenesis, and possible therapeutic targets and strategies. Expert Opin Ther Targets. 2023 Jul-Dec;27(12):1271-1284. doi: 10.1080/14728222.2023.2199923. Epub 2023 Jun 19. PMID: 37334903."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48968"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14862"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48968"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T11:16:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T11:16:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7553"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63514"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt"